# TypeScript Strict Hardening

Additional correctness flags recommended on top of `strict: true` for production TypeScript projects.

## Recommended flags

Enable these in `compilerOptions`:

- `noUncheckedIndexedAccess`: Forces `T | undefined` on index signatures. Prevents "undefined at runtime" from bracket access on arrays and records.
- `exactOptionalPropertyTypes`: Distinguishes `{ x?: string }` from `{ x: string | undefined }`. Catches misuse of optional properties vs explicit undefined assignment.
- `noImplicitOverride`: Requires the `override` keyword when overriding base class methods. Prevents silent breakage when a base class changes signatures.
- `useUnknownInCatchVariables`: Types `catch(e)` as `unknown` instead of `any`. Forces explicit narrowing in error handlers.

## Recommended target and lib

- `target`: `ES2024` (or latest stable supported by the runtime).
- `lib`: `["DOM", "DOM.Iterable", "ES2024"]`.
- `module`: `ESNext` with `moduleResolution`: `Bundler` for Next.js / Vite projects.

## Operational notes

- `skipLibCheck: true` stays on for productivity; it does not reduce safety in your own code.
- `incremental: true` for faster rebuilds.
- Run `/brp-code-quality` for the full `tsconfig.json` template.
